VALUES
(43, 11, 11, 43, 11, 43, 44, 'Lazarus sleepeth', 'Lazarus'' Sleep and Awakening', 'This connection highlights the theme of sleep and awakening, as Jesus refers to Lazarus as ''sleepeth'' in the source verse and then commands him to ''come forth'' in the target passage. Both passages emphasize the transition from death to life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 11, 46, 15, 51, 51, 'sleepeth', 'Connection of Sleep and Change', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''sleep'' as a metaphor for death in both passages. In John 11:11, Lazarus is described as sleeping, while 1 Corinthians 15:51 contrasts this with the idea of transformation, indicating a shift from death to life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 11, 52, 5, 10, 10, 'sleepeth', 'Connection of Sleep and Wakefulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of sleep as a metaphor for death in both passages. In John 11:11, Lazarus is described as sleeping, while 1 Thessalonians 5:10 contrasts waking and sleeping in the context of life with Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 11, 2, 33, 11, 11, 'Our friend Lazarus', 'Friendship and Divine Communication', 'This connection highlights the theme of friendship in both passages. Lazarus is referred to as ''Our friend'' in John, while Moses speaks to the Lord ''as a man speaketh unto his friend'' in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 13, 40, 9, 24, 24, NULL, 'Death and Sleep Motif', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of death as sleep. In John, Jesus speaks of death in terms of sleep, while in Matthew, he uses the same metaphor to describe the girl''s state, indicating a similar understanding of death.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 14, 43, 10, 24, 24, NULL, 'Plain Speech of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus speaking plainly. In John 10:24, the Jews ask Jesus to tell them plainly if he is the Christ, while in John 11:14, Jesus speaks plainly about Lazarus''s death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 14, 43, 16, 25, 25, NULL, 'Plain Speech of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' transition from speaking in proverbs to speaking plainly. In both passages, Jesus emphasizes clarity in communication, first regarding Lazarus'' death and later about the Father.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 14, 43, 16, 29, 29, NULL, 'Plain Speech of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the clarity of Jesus'' communication. In both passages, the emphasis is on Jesus speaking plainly, first about Lazarus'' death and then acknowledged by the disciples.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 55, 2, 10, 10, 'for your sakes', 'Connection of Endurance for Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring challenges for the sake of others'' faith and salvation. Both passages emphasize actions taken for the benefit of others to strengthen belief and attain eternal glory.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 43, 14, 10, 11, 'to the intent ye may believe', 'Connection of Belief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in Jesus'' divine relationship with the Father. In both passages, the emphasis is on believing in Jesus for the works He performs and the relationship He has with the Father.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 23, 54, 15, 15, 'let us go unto him', 'Gathering for Belief and Protection', 'This connection highlights the theme of gathering for a purpose, where John emphasizes belief through Jesus'' actions, while Isaiah speaks of those who gather against God''s people. Both passages suggest that gatherings, whether for faith or opposition, have significant consequences for the faithful.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 23, 65, 8, 8, 'for your sakes', 'Connection of Blessing and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of preservation for the sake of others. In both passages, the intent to protect and bless is emphasized, whether for belief in Jesus or for the servants of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 43, 2, 11, 11, NULL, 'Belief in Jesus'' Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in Jesus'' power. In both passages, the acts of Jesus lead to a deeper faith among his followers, as seen in the disciples'' belief following the miracles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 1, 26, 24, 24, NULL, 'Divine Presence and Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize God''s presence and assurance. In John, Jesus expresses gladness for the belief that will arise, while in Genesis, God reassures Isaac of His presence and blessings for Abraham''s sake.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 15, 1, 39, 5, 5, 'for your sakes', 'Blessing for Others'' Sake', 'This connection highlights the theme of blessings bestowed for the sake of others. In both passages, the actions of individuals lead to blessings that benefit those around them, emphasizing the impact of one''s presence or role.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 40, 10, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Thomas in the Gospels', 'Both passages emphasize Thomas''s presence among the disciples. In John 11:16, Thomas expresses a willingness to follow Jesus, while Matthew 10:3 lists him as one of the twelve disciples.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 43, 13, 37, 37, 'that we may die with him', 'Expressions of Willingness to Die', 'This connection highlights the theme of willingness to sacrifice oneself for a leader. Both Thomas and Peter express a readiness to lay down their lives, demonstrating loyalty and commitment to Jesus. Their statements reflect a shared sentiment of devotion in the face of danger.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 40, 26, 35, 35, 'that we may die with him', 'Disciples'' Willingness to Die', 'This connection highlights the theme of the disciples'' readiness to face death for Jesus. Both Thomas and Peter express a willingness to die alongside Him, showcasing their loyalty and commitment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 41, 3, 18, 18, 'Let us also go, that we may die with him.', 'Thomas as a Disciple', 'Both passages emphasize Thomas''s role as a disciple. In John 11:16, Thomas expresses a willingness to follow Jesus even unto death, while Mark 3:18 lists him among the chosen disciples.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 42, 6, 15, 15, 'Let us also go, that we may die with him.', 'Connection of Thomas in the Gospels', 'This connection highlights the presence of Thomas in both passages. In John, Thomas expresses a willingness to die with Jesus, while in Luke, he is listed among the disciples, indicating his role in the group.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 43, 21, 2, 2, 'Thomas, which is called Didymus', 'Thomas'' Presence in Both Passages', 'Both passages emphasize Thomas, called Didymus, indicating his ongoing role among the disciples. His mention in both contexts highlights his presence and participation in significant moments with the group.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 16, 42, 22, 33, 33, 'that we may die with him', 'Expressions of Willingness to Die', 'Both passages emphasize a readiness to face death for the sake of Jesus. Thomas expresses a willingness to die with Him, while Peter declares his readiness to go to death for Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 17, 43, 11, 39, 39, NULL, 'Connection of Lazarus'' Death', 'Both passages emphasize the duration of Lazarus'' death, specifically noting that he had been dead four days. This detail underscores the finality of his condition before Jesus intervenes.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 17, 28, 6, 2, 2, NULL, 'Resurrection Themes in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of revival and resurrection. John 11:17 mentions a four-day period before Jesus raises Lazarus, while Hosea 6:2 speaks of revival after two days and resurrection on the third day.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 17, 44, 2, 27, 31, 'four days already', 'Connection of Resurrection Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection, as both passages address the state of the dead. John 11:17 notes Lazarus has been dead for four days, while Acts 2:27-31 emphasizes that Christ''s flesh did not see corruption, indicating a victorious resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 17, 43, 2, 19, 19, NULL, 'Resurrection Timing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection timing, with Jesus referencing a three-day period for His own resurrection in John 2:19, while John 11:17 notes Lazarus had been dead for four days. Both passages emphasize the significance of time in relation to resurrection events.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 18, 66, 14, 20, 20, 'fifteen furlongs off', 'Distance from Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the geographical significance of distance in both passages. John mentions Bethany''s proximity to Jerusalem, while Revelation describes a vast distance in furlongs, emphasizing the separation from the city.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 18, 43, 6, 19, 19, 'fifteen furlongs off', 'Distance and Movement in Context', 'Both passages emphasize distance in relation to movement. In John 11:18, Bethany is described as being ''about fifteen furlongs off'' from Jerusalem, while John 6:19 mentions rowing ''about five and twenty or thirty furlongs'' on the sea, highlighting the significance of distance in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 18, 43, 11, 1, 1, 'Bethany was nigh unto Jerusalem', 'Location of Bethany', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Bethany, which is significant as it is the home of Lazarus, Mary, and Martha. The proximity of Bethany to Jerusalem, mentioned in the source verse, sets the stage for the events surrounding Lazarus''s illness and subsequent resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 18, 66, 21, 16, 16, 'fifteen furlongs off', 'Measurement and Distance in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the significance of measurement in both passages. John 11:18 mentions a specific distance of ''fifteen furlongs,'' while Revelation 21:16 describes the city measured at ''twelve thousand furlongs,'' emphasizing the theme of spatial dimensions in biblical narratives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
