(43, 11, 39, 41, 16, 3, 3, 'Take ye away the stone', 'Stone Removal in Resurrection Context', 'Both passages emphasize the act of removing a stone, which is central to the events surrounding death and resurrection. In John, Jesus commands the stone to be taken away from Lazarus'' tomb, while in Mark, the women question who will roll away the stone from Jesus'' tomb.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 1, 3, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Death and Decay', 'This connection highlights the theme of death and its consequences. In John 11:39, Martha acknowledges the physical decay of her brother, while Genesis 3:19 speaks to humanity''s return to dust after death.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 50, 3, 21, 21, 'he stinketh: for he hath been dead four days', 'Resurrection and Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation from death to life. In John 11:39, the concern about decay contrasts with the promise in Philippians 3:21 of a glorious body, emphasizing the power of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 1, 23, 4, 4, NULL, 'Death and Burial Connections', 'Both passages emphasize the reality of death and the need for burial. In John, Martha expresses concern about the decay of her brother, while in Genesis, the request for a burial place highlights the importance of honoring the dead.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 39, 44, 2, 27, 27, 'for he hath been dead four days', 'Connection of Corruption and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of corruption associated with death. In John 11:39, Martha expresses concern about the decay of Lazarus, while Acts 2:27 speaks of not allowing the Holy One to see corruption, emphasizing the contrast between Jesus'' resurrection and physical death.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 43, 11, 4, 4, 'glory of God', 'Connection of God''s Glory', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the glory of God. In John 11:4, Jesus indicates that the situation serves to reveal God''s glory, while in John 11:40, he connects belief with witnessing that glory.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 43, 11, 23, 26, 'if thou wouldest believe', 'Connection of Belief and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in Jesus for experiencing the glory of God and the promise of resurrection. Martha''s acknowledgment of the resurrection aligns with Jesus'' assertion that belief leads to seeing God''s glory.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 45, 4, 17, 25, 'if thou wouldest believe', 'Faith and Belief in God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in God''s promises. In John 11:40, Jesus highlights that belief leads to witnessing God''s glory, while Romans 4 discusses Abraham''s faith in God''s ability to fulfill His promises, despite seemingly impossible circumstances.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 19, 63, 2, 2, 'see the glory of God', 'Seeing God''s Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing God''s glory through belief and experience. Both passages emphasize the importance of seeing God''s power and glory, linking belief in Jesus to the experience of divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 14, 20, 20, 20, 'if thou wouldest believe', 'Faith and Divine Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in God as a means to witness His glory and receive His blessings. John 11:40 speaks of seeing the glory of God through belief, while 2 Chronicles 20:20 connects belief in God with establishment and prosperity.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 19, 90, 16, 16, 'see the glory of God', 'Connection of God''s Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing God''s glory through belief and service. Both passages emphasize the manifestation of God''s glory to those who believe and serve Him.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 40, 47, 3, 18, 18, 'see the glory of God', 'Seeing the Glory of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing God''s glory through belief and transformation. Both passages emphasize the importance of faith in experiencing divine glory, with John focusing on belief leading to sight and 2 Corinthians on beholding and being changed into that glory.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 40, 11, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Thankfulness to God', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus expressing gratitude to the Father. This connection highlights the theme of recognizing God''s authority and action in different contexts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 43, 17, 1, 1, 'lifted up his eyes', 'Connection of Prayer and Glorification', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus lifting up his eyes to heaven while addressing the Father. This connection highlights the theme of prayer and the relationship between Jesus and God in moments of significant events.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 19, 123, 1, 1, 'lifted up his eyes', 'Connection of Lifting Eyes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of lifting up one''s eyes, suggesting a focus on divine communication and presence. In John 11:41, Jesus lifts his eyes to thank the Father, while Psalms 123:1 expresses a similar act of looking towards God in heaven.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 42, 10, 21, 21, NULL, 'Thankfulness to the Father', 'This connection highlights the theme of thankfulness expressed by Jesus in both passages. In John 11:41, Jesus thanks the Father for being heard, while in Luke 10:21, He thanks the Father for revealing truths to the humble.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 43, 12, 28, 30, 'Father, I thank thee that thou hast heard me', 'Divine Communication and Glory', 'Both passages emphasize communication with the Father, highlighting Jesus'' relationship with God. In John 11:41, Jesus thanks the Father for hearing him, while in John 12:28, he requests that the Father glorify His name, leading to a divine response.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 50, 4, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Prayer and Thanksgiving', 'This connection highlights the importance of prayer and thanksgiving in approaching God. In both passages, the act of giving thanks is emphasized as part of communication with God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 41, 42, 18, 13, 13, 'lifted up his eyes', 'Connection of Prayer and Humility', 'This connection highlights the contrasting attitudes in prayer. In John 11:41, Jesus lifts his eyes in gratitude, while in Luke 18:13, the publican does not lift his eyes, demonstrating humility in his plea for mercy.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 43, 3, 17, 17, 'that they may believe that thou hast sent me', 'Connection of Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in God''s mission. Both passages emphasize that Jesus'' actions are intended to foster belief in Him as sent by God for salvation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 43, 17, 21, 21, NULL, 'Unity and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in relation to unity. Both passages emphasize that the unity among believers is intended to lead others to believe in Jesus'' divine mission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 62, 4, 14, 14, 'that thou hast sent me', 'Connection of Divine Sending', 'This connection highlights the theme of God sending His Son. Both passages emphasize the relationship between the Father and the Son, affirming the Son''s divine mission.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 40, 26, 53, 53, 'hearest me always', 'Prayer and Divine Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of prayer and divine intervention. Both passages emphasize the ability to call upon God for assistance, with John 11:42 indicating a relationship of trust in God''s responsiveness, while Matthew 26:53 suggests immediate divine aid through prayer.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 45, 8, 3, 3, 'that thou hast sent me', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. In John 11:42, Jesus emphasizes that God hears Him, affirming His divine mission, while Romans 8:3 speaks to God''s action through His Son, demonstrating His authority over sin.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 58, 5, 7, 7, 'that thou hast sent me', 'Connection of Prayer and Response', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being heard in prayer. John 11:42 highlights the assurance of being heard, while Hebrews 5:7 speaks of prayers offered with strong emotion that were also heard.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 42, 58, 7, 25, 25, 'that they may believe that thou hast sent me', 'Intercession and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of intercession in both passages. In John 11:42, the act of speaking to God is tied to belief, while Hebrews 7:25 emphasizes the ongoing intercession of Christ for believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 43, 12, 4, 33, 36, 'come forth', 'Resurrection and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the act of calling someone back to life. In John 11:43, Jesus commands Lazarus to come forth, while in 2 Kings 4:36, Elisha calls the Shunammite woman to take up her son after he is restored to life.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 43, 44, 9, 40, 40, NULL, 'Resurrection Commands', 'Both passages emphasize a command to rise from death. In John, Jesus calls Lazarus to come forth, while Peter commands Tabitha to arise, showcasing the power of spoken words in resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 43, 44, 9, 34, 34, NULL, 'Resurrection and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the command to arise, highlighting the power of Jesus to restore life and health. Lazarus is called forth from death, while Eneas is instructed to arise and be healed.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 43, 11, 17, 21, 22, 'come forth', 'Resurrection and Revival', 'Both passages emphasize the act of calling someone back to life. In John 11:43, Jesus commands Lazarus to come forth, while in 1 Kings 17:21-22, Elijah prays for the child''s soul to return.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
