VALUES
(43, 11, 43, 42, 7, 14, 15, NULL, 'Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the command to arise from death. In John, Jesus calls Lazarus to come forth, while in Luke, Jesus tells the young man to arise, resulting in both being restored to life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 43, 41, 4, 41, 41, NULL, 'Authority Over Life and Nature', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus over both life and nature. In John 11:43, Jesus commands Lazarus to come forth, demonstrating his power over death, while in Mark 4:41, the disciples marvel at his ability to command the wind and sea, showing his dominion over creation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 43, 5, 25, 25, NULL, 'Resurrection and Life Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection, as both passages discuss the dead responding to the voice of Jesus. In John 11:44, Lazarus is raised from the dead, while John 5:25 speaks of the dead hearing His voice and living.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 43, 20, 7, 7, 'with graveclothes: and his face was bound about with a napkin', 'Connection of Graveclothes and Napkin', 'This connection highlights the presence of graveclothes and a napkin in both passages. In John 11:44, the dead man is described as being bound with graveclothes, while John 20:7 specifically mentions the napkin about Jesus'' head, emphasizing the significance of these burial wrappings.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 42, 7, 15, 15, 'he that was dead', 'Resurrection and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the act of raising the dead, showcasing Jesus'' authority over death. In John, Lazarus comes forth bound, while in Luke, the young man sits up and speaks, indicating restoration to life.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 50, 3, 21, 21, 'he that was dead came forth', 'Transformation of the Body', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation from death to life. In John 11:44, Lazarus is raised from the dead, while Philippians 3:21 speaks of changing our vile body to a glorious one, emphasizing the power of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 1, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'Light and Life Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation from death to life. In John 11:44, the act of Jesus calling Lazarus forth parallels God''s command in Genesis 1:3, where light emerges from darkness, symbolizing new beginnings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 9, 2, 6, 6, NULL, 'Resurrection and Divine Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of life and death, highlighting God''s authority to bring individuals back to life. John 11:44 illustrates Jesus'' power to resurrect Lazarus, while 1 Samuel 2:6 states that the Lord brings people up from the grave.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 44, 44, 20, 9, 12, NULL, 'Resurrection and Restoration', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection, as both passages describe individuals who were dead and then brought back to life. In John 11:44, Lazarus is called forth from the grave, while in Acts 20:9-12, Eutychus is restored to life after falling. Both instances emphasize the power of God to restore life.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 2, 23, 23, 'believed on him', 'Belief in Jesus through Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize belief in Jesus resulting from witnessing miracles. In John 11:45, many believed after seeing what Jesus did, paralleling John 2:23 where belief arose from observing his miracles.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 11, 19, 19, 'many of the Jews', 'Connection of Belief and Comfort', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of many Jews who came to support Martha and Mary, and later, those who believed in Jesus after witnessing his actions. This connection highlights the communal aspect of grief and faith in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 7, 31, 31, 'believed on him', 'Belief in Jesus'' Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the belief of the people in Jesus due to the miracles he performed. The mention of belief in John 11:45 connects directly to the inquiry about Jesus'' miracles in John 7:31.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 10, 41, 41, 'believed on him', 'Belief in Jesus'' Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the belief in Jesus based on the testimonies of others. In John 11:45, many believed after witnessing Jesus'' miracles, while in John 10:41, people acknowledged the truth of John''s words about Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 11, 31, 31, NULL, 'Response to Mourning and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of the Jews to Marys actions. In John 11:31, they follow her, believing she is going to weep, while in John 11:45, many of them believe in Jesus after witnessing His miracle.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 12, 9, 11, 'believed on him', 'Belief in Jesus and Lazarus', 'Both passages emphasize the belief of many Jews in Jesus due to the miraculous raising of Lazarus. The SOURCE verse notes that many believed on him after witnessing his works, while the TARGET passage shows that many came to see Lazarus, leading to further belief in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 45, 43, 12, 17, 19, 'believed on him', 'Belief in Jesus'' Miracles', 'This connection highlights how the belief of many Jews in Jesus, as noted in John 11:45, is reinforced in John 12:17-19, where those who witnessed Lazarus'' resurrection bear record of this miracle. Both passages emphasize the impact of Jesus'' miraculous acts on the people''s faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 46, 43, 9, 13, 13, 'the Pharisees', 'Connection to the Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the involvement of the Pharisees in both narratives. In John 11:46, individuals report Jesus'' actions to the Pharisees, while in John 9:13, a man healed by Jesus is brought to them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 46, 42, 16, 30, 31, 'what things Jesus had done', 'Response to Jesus'' Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief despite miraculous signs. In John, the Pharisees hear of Jesus'' deeds but do not believe, paralleling the idea in Luke that even if someone rises from the dead, they may not be persuaded.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 46, 43, 5, 15, 16, 'told them what things Jesus had done', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the response of the Jews to Jesus'' actions. In John 11:46, some went to inform the Pharisees about Jesus, while in John 5:15-16, the man tells the Jews about Jesus healing him, leading to persecution.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 46, 43, 12, 37, 37, NULL, 'Unbelief Despite Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in Jesus despite the miracles he performed. In both passages, the actions of Jesus and the response of the people are contrasted, emphasizing their refusal to believe.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 46, 44, 5, 25, 25, 'went their ways to the Pharisees', 'Reporting Actions of Jesus and Apostles', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals reporting significant actions to authorities. In both passages, people inform the Pharisees and the authorities about the activities of Jesus and the apostles, respectively.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 40, 26, 3, 3, 'chief priests', 'Gathering of Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of chief priests to discuss Jesus. In John, they are concerned about his miracles, while in Matthew, they assemble to plot against him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 40, 5, 22, 22, NULL, 'Judgment and Council Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and the council''s role in both passages. In John 11:47, the council is concerned about the miracles, while in Matthew 5:22, being in danger of the council relates to judgment for anger.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 43, 2, 11, 11, 'many miracles', 'Connection of Miracles in John', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' miracles. In John 2:11, the miracles are presented as a manifestation of His glory, while in John 11:47, the miracles prompt concern among the religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 43, 11, 57, 57, 'this man doeth many miracles', 'Plot Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of the chief priests and Pharisees in response to Jesus'' miracles. The first passage shows their concern about what to do regarding his miracles, while the second reveals their command to capture him, indicating a direct escalation in their plot against him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 44, 4, 5, 6, NULL, 'Gathering of Religious Leaders', 'This connection highlights the gathering of religious authorities in response to perceived threats. Both passages depict a council or assembly of leaders concerned about the actions of Jesus and his followers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 44, 4, 16, 17, 'many miracles', 'Miracles and Responses', 'This connection highlights the theme of miracles prompting significant reactions from religious leaders. Both passages reflect the concern of authorities regarding notable miracles and their implications for control over the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 47, 19, 2, 2, 4, 'gathered the chief priests and the Pharisees a council', 'Counsel Against the Anointed', 'This connection highlights the gathering of rulers to plot against a significant figure. Both passages emphasize the act of taking counsel against the Lord and His anointed, showcasing a theme of opposition to divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 48, 40, 23, 35, 38, 'our place and nation', 'Desolation and Judgment Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of impending judgment on Jerusalem for rejecting God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the consequences of disbelief and the loss of their place and nation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 48, 40, 27, 25, 25, 'our place and nation', 'Consequences of Jesus'' Influence', 'This connection highlights the fear of losing ''our place and nation'' in John 11:48, which resonates with the people''s declaration in Matthew 27:25 of accepting responsibility for Jesus'' blood. Both passages emphasize the perceived threat to national identity and stability due to Jesus'' influence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
